---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
---
<Base title="Human-Centered, Robot-Driven: Ethical Considerations for AI in Design · uxward">
  <style>
    .read-bar {
      position: fixed;
      top: 0; left: 0;
      height: 2px;
      width: 0%;
      background: var(--signature);
      z-index: 200;
      transition: width 80ms linear;
    }

    .reading-column {
      max-width: 660px;
      margin: 0 auto;
      padding: 0 var(--gutter-x);
    }

    .essay-top { padding: var(--space-8) 0 var(--space-7); }
    .essay-top .row {
      display: flex;
      align-items: baseline;
      justify-content: space-between;
      gap: var(--space-7);
      flex-wrap: wrap;
    }
    .essay-top a.back,
    .essay-top .meta {
      font-family: var(--font-mono);
      font-size: 11px;
      letter-spacing: 0.2em;
      text-transform: uppercase;
      color: var(--tertiary);
      text-decoration: none;
    }
    .essay-top a.back:hover { color: var(--ink); }
    .essay-top .meta .sep { padding: 0 12px; color: var(--rule); }

    .essay-title-block { padding: var(--space-9) 0 var(--space-10); }
    .essay-title {
      font-family: var(--font-serif);
      font-weight: 300;
      font-size: clamp(42px, 5.6vw, 76px);
      line-height: 1.02;
      letter-spacing: -0.025em;
      font-variation-settings: 'opsz' 144, 'SOFT' 30;
      color: var(--ink);
      margin: 0;
      max-width: 820px;
    }
    .essay-title em {
      font-style: italic; font-weight: 400;
      font-variation-settings: 'opsz' 144, 'SOFT' 100, 'WONK' 1;
    }
    .essay-deck {
      font-family: var(--font-serif);
      font-style: italic;
      font-weight: 300;
      font-size: 22px;
      line-height: 1.45;
      color: var(--body);
      margin: var(--space-7) 0 0;
      max-width: 660px;
      font-variation-settings: 'opsz' 36, 'SOFT' 80, 'WONK' 1;
    }
    .essay-byline {
      font-family: var(--font-mono);
      font-size: 11px;
      letter-spacing: 0.22em;
      text-transform: uppercase;
      color: var(--tertiary);
      margin-top: var(--space-8);
    }

    .essay-body { padding: var(--space-9) 0 var(--space-10); }
    .essay-body p {
      font-family: var(--font-serif);
      font-weight: 400;
      font-size: 18px;
      line-height: 1.65;
      color: var(--body);
      max-width: 660px;
      margin: 0 0 var(--space-6);
      font-variation-settings: 'opsz' 14;
      text-wrap: pretty;
    }
    .essay-body p strong { font-weight: 500; color: var(--ink); }
    .essay-body p em { font-style: italic; }
    .essay-body p:first-of-type::first-letter {
      font-family: var(--font-serif);
      font-weight: 300;
      font-size: 5.2em;
      line-height: 0.88;
      float: left;
      padding: 6px 12px 0 0;
      color: var(--ink);
      font-variation-settings: 'opsz' 144, 'SOFT' 30, 'WONK' 1;
    }
    .essay-body h2 {
      font-family: var(--font-serif);
      font-weight: 400;
      font-size: 30px;
      line-height: 1.18;
      letter-spacing: -0.015em;
      color: var(--ink);
      margin: var(--space-10) 0 var(--space-7);
      font-variation-settings: 'opsz' 96, 'SOFT' 50;
      max-width: 660px;
    }
    .essay-body h2 em {
      font-style: italic; font-weight: 400;
      font-variation-settings: 'opsz' 96, 'SOFT' 100, 'WONK' 1;
    }
    .essay-body blockquote {
      font-family: var(--font-serif);
      font-style: italic;
      font-weight: 300;
      font-size: 26px;
      line-height: 1.35;
      color: var(--ink);
      border-left: 3px solid var(--signature);
      padding: 4px 0 4px var(--space-7);
      margin: var(--space-9) 0;
      max-width: 600px;
      font-variation-settings: 'opsz' 96, 'SOFT' 100, 'WONK' 1;
    }
    .essay-body figure { margin: var(--space-9) 0; }
    .essay-body figure img { max-width: 100%; height: auto; display: block; }
    .essay-body figure figcaption {
      font-family: var(--font-mono);
      font-size: 11px;
      letter-spacing: 0.1em;
      color: var(--tertiary);
      margin-top: var(--space-4);
    }

    .essay-end {
      margin-top: var(--space-9);
      padding-top: var(--space-7);
      border-top: 1px solid var(--rule);
    }
    .essay-end .author {
      font-family: var(--font-mono);
      font-size: 11px;
      letter-spacing: 0.22em;
      text-transform: uppercase;
      color: var(--tertiary);
      margin-top: var(--space-6);
    }

    .more {
      border-top: 1px solid var(--rule);
      padding: var(--space-10) 0 var(--space-9);
    }
    .more .more-eyebrow {
      font-family: var(--font-mono);
      font-size: 11px;
      letter-spacing: 0.22em;
      text-transform: uppercase;
      color: var(--tertiary);
      margin-bottom: var(--space-8);
    }
    .more-grid {
      display: grid;
      grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr 1fr;
      gap: var(--space-9);
    }
    .more-grid .essay-card {
      text-decoration: none; color: inherit; display: block;
    }
    .more-grid .essay-card .meta {
      font-family: var(--font-mono);
      font-size: 11px;
      letter-spacing: 0.2em;
      text-transform: uppercase;
      color: var(--tertiary);
      margin-bottom: var(--space-5);
    }
    .more-grid .essay-card .title {
      font-family: var(--font-serif);
      font-weight: 400;
      font-size: 22px;
      line-height: 1.22;
      letter-spacing: -0.015em;
      color: var(--ink);
      font-variation-settings: 'opsz' 48, 'SOFT' 50;
      margin: 0 0 var(--space-3);
    }
    .more-grid .essay-card .deck {
      font-family: var(--font-serif);
      font-style: italic;
      font-size: 16.5px;
      line-height: 1.5;
      color: var(--body);
      margin: 0;
      font-variation-settings: 'opsz' 24, 'SOFT' 80, 'WONK' 1;
    }
    .more-grid .essay-card:hover .title { color: var(--tertiary); }

    .all-link { margin-top: var(--space-9); }
    .all-link a {
      font-family: var(--font-serif);
      font-size: 18px;
      color: var(--ink);
      text-decoration: underline;
      text-underline-offset: 4px;
      text-decoration-thickness: 1px;
    }

    @media (max-width: 720px) {
      .more-grid { grid-template-columns: 1fr; gap: var(--space-8); }
    }
  </style>

  <div class="read-bar" id="read-bar" aria-hidden="true"></div>

  <div class="reading-column essay-top">
    <div class="row">
      <a class="back" href="/writing">— Back to writing</a>
      <div class="meta">
        <span>Q1 2023</span>
        <span class="sep">·</span>
        <span>Essay</span>
        <span class="sep">·</span>
        <span>11 min read</span>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="reading-column essay-title-block">
    <h1 class="essay-title">
      Human-Centered, <em>Robot-Driven:</em> Ethical Considerations for AI in Design
    </h1>
    <p class="essay-deck">
      Machine learning is reshaping how we build products. The ethical obligations that come with that power belong to designers as much as anyone.
    </p>
    <div class="essay-byline">— By Brandon E. B. Ward —</div>
  </div>

  <article class="reading-column essay-body">

    <figure>
      <img src="/images/writing/ai-ethics-header.jpg" alt="AI ethics concept illustration" />
    </figure>

    <p>
      Artificial intelligence is no longer a science fiction premise or a research lab curiosity. It is in the products we ship, the interfaces we design, and the decisions we help automate. Which means the ethical weight of machine learning now sits — at least in part — on the shoulders of designers.
    </p>

    <p>
      That is not a comfortable realization. Designers are trained to advocate for users. We are trained to make things usable and useful. We are not trained to audit training datasets or interrogate model architectures. But the products we design are increasingly built on those foundations, and what we put in front of users shapes what they trust, what they fear, and what opportunities they have access to.
    </p>

    <figure>
      <img src="/images/writing/thingamabob.jpg" alt="A mysterious machine — the opacity of algorithmic systems" />
    </figure>

    <h2>The opacity problem</h2>

    <p>
      One of the defining characteristics of machine learning systems is that they are opaque. A traditional rules-based system is auditable: you can read the code, trace the logic, find the bug. A trained model is a black box. It produces outputs, but the reasoning that produced them is not legible to human inspection in any straightforward way.
    </p>

    <p>
      This creates a design problem: how do you design an interface for a system whose outputs you cannot fully explain? When users ask "why did it recommend this?" or "why was my application rejected?" or "why does this content keep appearing?" — what does the interface say?
    </p>

    <p>
      Explainability is an ethical obligation. Not just a UX nicety. Users have a right to understand consequential decisions made about them, especially in high-stakes domains like healthcare, finance, employment, and housing.
    </p>

    <figure>
      <img src="/images/writing/bad-actor.jpg" alt="Bad actor illustration — AI misuse" />
    </figure>

    <h2>Bad actors and foreseeable misuse</h2>

    <p>
      Every powerful tool has foreseeable misuse cases. A hammer can break a skull as easily as drive a nail. The designer of the hammer is not culpable for that misuse — but the designer of an AI system that can generate convincing fake identities, automate targeted harassment, or make discriminatory decisions at scale bears a different kind of responsibility. The misuse was foreseeable. The design choices either mitigated it or enabled it.
    </p>

    <p>
      Design teams working on AI products need to run threat modeling as part of their process. Not just: "What do we want users to do?" but "What would a bad actor do with this, and how does our design respond?" Red-teaming is not just for security engineers. It belongs in the design process.
    </p>

    <figure>
      <img src="/images/writing/bias-yin-yang.jpg" alt="Bias in AI — the yin and yang of data" />
    </figure>

    <h2>Bias is a design problem</h2>

    <p>
      Algorithmic bias is well-documented and well-studied at this point. Facial recognition systems that perform significantly worse on darker skin tones. Hiring algorithms that penalize gaps in employment history disproportionately common among caregivers. Credit models that encode historical redlining into their risk scores.
    </p>

    <p>
      These are not just engineering failures. They are design failures. The teams that built these systems made choices — about what data to use, what outcomes to optimize for, what success metrics to measure — and those choices had disparate impacts on different groups of people.
    </p>

    <figure>
      <img src="/images/writing/uxward_thief_in_black_stealing_a_painting.png" alt="The theft of consent — data used without permission" />
    </figure>

    <p>
      Designers have leverage at several points in this chain. In defining success metrics: are we measuring accuracy for the average user, or are we auditing for differential performance across demographic groups? In user research: are our research participants representative of the full population our system will affect? In the interface: are we surfacing model uncertainty and limitations honestly, or are we presenting outputs as more authoritative than they are?
    </p>

    <h2>Recommended reading</h2>

    <figure>
      <img src="/images/writing/weapons-of-math-destruction.jpg" alt="Weapons of Math Destruction by Cathy O'Neil" />
    </figure>

    <p>
      Cathy O'Neil's <em>Weapons of Math Destruction</em> is essential reading for anyone building AI-powered products. O'Neil documents how large-scale algorithmic systems — in education, employment, criminal justice, credit — consistently harm the people least equipped to push back. The systems are opaque, they optimize for proxies rather than actual outcomes, and they are self-reinforcing in ways that compound disadvantage over time.
    </p>

    <figure>
      <img src="/images/writing/technically-wrong.jpg" alt="Technically Wrong by Sara Wachter-Boettcher" />
    </figure>

    <p>
      Sara Wachter-Boettcher's <em>Technically Wrong</em> examines how the demographics of the tech industry — who is in the room, who is not — shape the products that get built and who they serve. The default assumptions baked into product design reflect the experiences of the people who made it. When those people are not representative of users, the products fail in predictable ways.
    </p>

    <h2>The obligation</h2>

    <figure>
      <img src="/images/writing/handshake.jpg" alt="A handshake — the designer's obligation to users" />
    </figure>

    <p>
      The designer's obligation has always been to advocate for users. In the age of AI, that obligation extends further: to advocate for users who are not in the room, whose experiences are underrepresented in the training data, whose needs were not considered when the success metrics were defined.
    </p>

    <blockquote>
      The ethical weight of machine learning belongs to designers as much as to engineers.
    </blockquote>

    <figure>
      <img src="/images/writing/robots-lift-us-up.jpg" alt="Robots that lift us up — the possibility of beneficial AI" />
    </figure>

    <p>
      None of this is an argument against AI in design. Machine learning has genuine potential to surface patterns humans miss, to personalize experiences in ways that make products more accessible and useful, to automate the tedious so designers can focus on the meaningful. But realizing that potential requires designers who take the ethical dimension of their work seriously — who ask hard questions before shipping, not after.
    </p>

    <div class="essay-end">
      <div class="author">— Brandon E. B. Ward · Dallas, TX —</div>
    </div>

  </article>

  <section class="container">
    <div class="more">
      <div class="grid">
        <div class="marker">§ ↗</div>
        <div>
          <div class="more-eyebrow">— More from the writing —</div>
          <div class="more-grid">
            <a class="essay-card" href="/writing">
              <div class="meta">— Essay —</div>
              <h3 class="title">More writing</h3>
              <p class="deck">Thoughts on design, leadership, and the work of making things for people.</p>
            </a>
            <a class="essay-card" href="/writing">
              <div class="meta">— Essay —</div>
              <h3 class="title">More writing</h3>
              <p class="deck">Thoughts on design, leadership, and the work of making things for people.</p>
            </a>
            <a class="essay-card" href="/writing">
              <div class="meta">— Essay —</div>
              <h3 class="title">More writing</h3>
              <p class="deck">Thoughts on design, leadership, and the work of making things for people.</p>
            </a>
          </div>
          <div class="all-link">
            <a href="/writing">— All writing →</a>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <script>
    (function () {
      var bar = document.getElementById('read-bar');
      if (!bar) return;
      function update() {
        var doc = document.documentElement;
        var max = (doc.scrollHeight - doc.clientHeight);
        var pct = max > 0 ? Math.min(100, Math.max(0, (doc.scrollTop || window.scrollY) / max * 100)) : 0;
        bar.style.width = pct + '%';
      }
      update();
      window.addEventListener('scroll', update, { passive: true });
      window.addEventListener('resize', update);
    })();
  </script>
</Base>
